> 2 sounds the least 'invasive' (we just need to add a line or two), and we can add a comment as well explaining the motivation.

Yes, it also raises a broader "parameter validation" question, e.g. to what extent should we verify that the supplied parameters to functions are the correct type, try to cast them when they aren't, and then throw helpful errors when they can't be cast?  That ends up being more than a line or two though, something like:

```Python
if not isinstance(beta2, float):
    try:
        beta2 = float(beta2)
    except:
        raise ValueError('beta2 must be a float, but {} was supplied'.format(beta2))
```
Of course, we could omit the first line as well as the try/except, depending on whether we are OK with people figuring out what the exception caused by `beta2 = float(beta2)` means by themselves.

I have been working on a PR to shore up the remaining differences between the two temporal memory implementations, while along the way fixing the serialization issue #3199 created by the change to columnSegmentWalk.  In the process I have run into some performance issues that, although I have not explored all options, might mean that this change will make the temporal memory implementation slower than the current implementation in nupic. On the other hand, I have verified that these implementations (after a slight change to nupic.core) perform exactly the same when fed in hotgym (This is not the case with the current implementation).

My question is do we value the parity of the two implementations over the speed of the python implementation?

