My question is not bout how you use your library keywords or where you call them. The question is about when you build the library keywords, on top of the SeleniumLibrary, why you want the `run on failure` be applied automatically? When I did build my library keyword, I did have other methods than just SeleniumLibrary methods and I did have some custom logic in those libraries which where not based on SeleniumLibrary. Example when I have a login, it is not just about entering the user name/password and pressing the login button. Login could involve example changing the user default password and/or creating a secret question(s) for the user. In pseudo code it could look like this: 
```
def login(self, username, passowrd):
    if not self.browser:
        self.sl.open_browser(self.url, "chrome")
    self._login()
    if self._password_change_visible():
        self._change_password()
    if self._secret_question_visible():
        self._set_secret_question()
   self.sl.location_should_hontain("home")
```
In that code, only the parts that are prefixed with `self.sl` are coming directly from SeleniumLibrary. So if those parts fail, the logs will have the  SL `run on failure` run but other parts not. Also SL parts may fail intentionally, so it will be flooding logs with  `run on failure` on those cases is not good idea in my mind. There I did build my own `run on failure` logic to my library keywords and if keyword fails, then keyword will trigger the run on failure and the run on failure is not triggered multiple times by different parts of lithe methods or libraries.

